# Budget Calculator

A responsive, interactive personal budget calculator built with vanilla HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.

https://razzy21.github.io/Budget-Calculator/

---

## What Problem It Solves

Most people track their budget in a spreadsheet — but spreadsheets aren't interactive, don't visualize your spending, and don't work well on mobile. This app gives anyone a fast, visual way to enter their income and expenses, see where their money is going, and track progress toward a savings goal — all without signing up or installing anything.

---

## Features

- **Income & expense tracking** — add, edit, and remove entries in real time
- **Category tags** — group expenses by Housing, Food, Transport, Health, Entertainment, and Other
- **Expense breakdown chart** — pie chart that groups spending by category with consistent colors
- **Savings goal tracker** — set a target savings rate and watch a color-coded progress bar update live
- **Monthly / Annual toggle** — switch between monthly and annual view of all totals
- **Currency selector** — supports ₦ Naira, $ Dollar, £ Pound, and € Euro
- **Dark mode** — full dark theme with preference saved to localStorage
- **Animated totals** — numbers count up smoothly when values change
- **Empty state guidance** — helpful prompts when lists are empty
- **Color-coded rows** — green tint for income, red tint for expenses
- **CSV export** — download your budget data as a spreadsheet
- **Auto-save** — data persists in localStorage between sessions
- **Responsive design** — works on mobile, tablet, and desktop

---

## Built With

- **HTML5** — semantic markup and accessibility attributes
- **CSS3** — CSS custom properties (variables) for theming, CSS Grid for layout, media queries for responsiveness
- **Vanilla JavaScript (ES6+)** — no frameworks, no dependencies
- **Chart.js** — pie chart for expense breakdown

---

## What I Learned

This project was my first substantial front-end build after transitioning from a non-technical background. Key things I picked up:

- **DOM manipulation** — building dynamic UI elements entirely in JavaScript without a framework
- **localStorage** — persisting app state across browser sessions
- **CSS variables** — using custom properties to power a full dark/light theme switch from a single class toggle
- **requestAnimationFrame** — implementing smooth number animations without any animation library
- **Debugging** — tracking down real bugs like a broken CSS `border` shorthand split across lines, a `\\n` vs `\n` CSV export issue, and a script loading order problem that silently killed all event listeners
- **Responsive design** — adapting a two-column desktop layout to stack cleanly on mobile

